description text
By the end of 2016, national capacity to legislate, budget and provide quality maternal and child nutrition services isstrengthened.
Central and decentralized health authorities in targeted areas have improved capacity to legislate, budget, design and deliverquality and equitable nutrition services.

Central and decentralized health and environment authorities in targeted areas have improved capacity to legislate, budget, design,deliver and coordinate WASH services and interventions to mitigate the impact of air pollution on child survival.

Central and decentralized health authorities in targeted areas have improved capacity to roll-out and sustain MHCH, STI/HIVprevention and adolescent mental health services, through established subnational delivery systems.
Effective and efficient management of operational resources and processes, including financial resources and administrative assets,to timely and adequately support programme results.
PRIOR-YEAR COMMITMENTS
UNICEF staff and partners are provided guidance, tools and resources for effective advocacy and partnerships on child rights issueswith stakeholders.
By the end of 2016, national and sub-national capacity to provide access to quality early childhood development services,especially for the most vulnerable children, is increased.
UNICEF staff and partners are provided guidance, tools and resources to effectively plan and monitor programmes

Effective and appropriate governance structures established, supported by efficient information technology and communicationsystems, to adequately support programme coordination including the Khuvsgul office.
Decentralized education authorities in target areas have improved capacity to increase access and utilization of quality, inclusiveECD and primary education services.

Education authorities in target areas have improved capacity to design and implement innovative programmes that can enhance lifeskills, participation and increase utilisation of STI prevention services.

The Ministry of Education, Culture and Science's capacity to develop, budget, design and implement equity-focused, gender-sensitivepolicies, strategies, norms, requirements for early childhood development, primary and adolescent learning is enhanced.
Increased coverage of children's issues from a child-rights perspective in the media (newspapers/radio/TV)
Education authorities in targeted areas have increased capacity to implement national norms and requirements for water, sanitationand hygiene in kindergartens, schools and dormitories.
By the end of the 2016, national capacity is strengthened in policy dialogue and advocacy for CSR and business practices thatrespect and support children's rights

Government's capacity to legislate, plan, budget and to provide child protection services has increased to protect children fromviolence, abuse and exploitation at central level and in targeted areas.

Local authorities in target areas have adopted child-friendly strategies, improved knowledge of the situation of children andenhanced capacity to design and deliver integrated and equitable supply of services.
National authorities have increased capacity and evidence to enhance the equity and child focus of the national social protectionsystem.
The private sector (and in particular extractive industries) has increased capacity and commitment to its responsibility to respectchild rights, including implementation of CRBP.
Effective and transparent procurement of goods and services, contract management and supply monitoring to adequately supportprogramme results.
